g><languageCode value="eng" Sync="TRUE"/><countryCode value="USA" Sync="TRUE"/></dataLang><idCitation xmlns=""><resTitle Sync="FALSE">Salzburg Plantae Biodiversity Density (CIVIS Pilot Site Case Study)</resTitle><presForm xmlns=""><PresFormCd value="001" Sync="FALSE"/><fgdcGeoform>document</fgdcGeoform></presForm><date><createDate>2026-06-17T00:00:00</createDate><pubDate>2026-06-17T00:00:00</pubDate><reviseDate>2026-06-18T00:00:00</reviseDate></date></idCitation><spatRpType><SpatRepTypCd value="001" Sync="TRUE"/></spatRpType><idPurp>This provides information on  Salzburg biodiversity of Plantae density. The primary purpose of documenting this metadata is to make newly created Salzburg biodiversity data layer discoverable, understandable, and reusable within our project’s Spatial Data Infrastructure (SDI) and the wider CIVIS university network.</idPurp><idCredit>Emmanuel Udeonwo and Group 4 team SDI Project</idCredit><searchKeys><keyword>Biodiversity</keyword><keyword>Plantae_Layer</keyword><keyword>Clipped_Salzburg Layer</keyword><keyword>Plantae</keyword><keyword>Salzburg</keyword><keyword>CIVIS</keyword></searchKeys><idAbs>&lt;DIV STYLE="text-align:Left;"&gt;&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;P&gt;&lt;SPAN&gt;This vector dataset represents the spatial density of botanical occurrences (Taxon: Plantae) within the administrative boundary of the Salzburg study area. The source occurrence data was extracted from the Biodiversity Database of the Haus der Natur Salzburg via the Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF) web portal. The raw point data was structurally aggregated into a 250m metric fishnet grid using ArcGIS Pro/QGIS spatial join tools to create an urban-scale indicator for "Cooling Vegetation Profile". This layer is a primary component of the HotEurope SDI project, serving to spatially cross-reference urban green assets against satellite-derived Land Surface Temperature (LST) rasters.&lt;/SPAN&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;</idAbs><idPoC xml